Hi Johnnie,

You can get a PDF of the report emailed to you when it runs.
To do this you just navigate to the report and select > configure. On the email page you can setup who the report will be emailed to and what format it will take.

You will have to have configured an email server though in the Settings > Notification area.

Thank you,

Hi Johnnie,

Port 587 is already using TLS encryption when connecting to an SMTP server.
This looks like an auth issue. From the server that is running the NEA console, can you run the below powershell command to test connectivity to the server?

tnc -ComputerName "smtp.gmail.com" -Port 587

Thank you,

TextBody:
Hi Johnny,

If we can't get authentication or an open relay setup, one other way you can get the report is to navigate to the report in the console and select configure.


From the configure, select widgets on the left side, then select the widget and select configure.



From the configure, enable the checkbox labeled "Export table data as CSV" and then hit ok.



Run the report again and when you view it, there will be an option to download the table data to a csv file that can be more easily printed.



Thank you,
Ian Ranstrom
Senior Technical Support Engineer

TextBody:
Hi Johnnie,

We don't really have a table that is specifically keeping track of the user OUs. You'd need more information about what the full DN looks like for one of these users to create the statement to generate the report.

Here is the documentation on creating custom views in NEA for the information you want.
https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/EnterpriseAuditor_11.6/page/Content/EnterpriseAuditor/Admin/Analysis/SQLViewCreation/Overview.htm

If you need help beyond this you would need to reach out to the professional service team to help create custom scripts as this is not something the support team can really do in depth for you.

Thank you,
Ian Ranstrom
Senior Technical Support Engineer

Subject: RE: Netwrix Support Ticket #426085 -  - [EXTERNAL] RE: 00426085 - Assistance creating a new report.    [ ref:!00D70091pB.!500Qk0Hud6Y:ref ]

TextBody:
Hi Johnnie,

OUs are just containers inside of AD and don't really have an effect on users directly. We can find the OU of users by finding their distinguished name and work from there, but the OU structure is not something that we track in NEA directly.

Groups and users are objects and we keep detailed info on them, so they are easier to look up. Your request is something that could be configured for a report, but since OUs are not static and I don't have information on your AD environment I can't provide you the scripts you'd like to create those reports. The professional service teams with Netwrix can help you setup more customized scripts for your environment though.

Thank you,
Ian Ranstrom
Senior Technical Support Engineer

Hi Johnnie,

OUs are just containers inside of AD and don't really have an effect on users directly. We can find the OU of users by finding their distinguished name and work from there, but the OU structure is not something that we track in NEA directly.

Groups and users are objects and we keep detailed info on them, so they are easier to look up. Your request is something that could be configured for a report, but since OUs are not static and I don't have information on your AD environment I can't provide you the scripts you'd like to create those reports. The professional service teams with Netwrix can help you setup more customized scripts for your environment though.

Hi Johnnie,

OUs are just containers inside of AD and don't really have an effect on users directly. We can find the OU of users by finding their distinguished name and work from there, but the OU structure is not something that we track in NEA directly.

Groups and users are objects and we keep detailed info on them, so they are easier to look up. Your request is something that could be configured for a report, but since OUs are not static and I don't have information on your AD environment I can't provide you the scripts you'd like to create those reports. The professional service teams with Netwrix can help you setup more customized scripts for your environment though.

Thank you,

Hi Johnnie,

OUs are just containers inside of AD and don't really have an effect on users directly. We can find the OU of users by finding their distinguished name and work from there, but the OU structure is not something that we track in NEA directly.

Groups and users are objects and we keep detailed info on them, so they are easier to look up. Your request is something that could be configured for a report, but since OUs are not static and I don't have information on your AD environment I can't provide you the scripts you'd like to create those reports. The professional service teams with Netwrix can help you setup more customized scripts for your environment though.

Thank you,
